## Flutter App Architecture & Coding Rules

### Purpose
A concise, repeatable blueprint for building maintainable Flutter applications with clear layering, predictable state, and testable code.

## Core Principles
- Prefer simple, explicit code in small classes in separate files.
- Keep UI, business logic, and data access separated.
- Make architectural choices consistent within the app.
- Optimize for readability, testability, and safe iteration.

## Standard Packages
- Use `flutter_bloc` with `Cubit` for feature state management.
- Use `get_it` for dependency injection.
- Use `go_router` for app routing.
- Use `equatable` for entities, state classes, and other value objects where value equality matters.

## Project Structure
- Use this repo structure under `lib/`:
  - `domain/entity/` for app entities.
  - `domain/usecase/` for business logic units.
  - `repository/` for repository implementations and coordination.
  - `data/` for remote, local, cache, network, and mapper code.
  - `di/` for `GetIt` registrations.
  - `router/` for `GoRouter` configuration.
  - `ui/screens/<feature>/` for feature UI.
  - `ui/screens/<feature>/viewmodel/` for the feature Cubit and its separate state file.
  - `ui/screens/<feature>/widgets/` for feature-specific widgets.
  - `ui/widgets/`, `ui/theme/`, and `ui/design_system/` for shared UI building blocks.
- Keep feature folder boundaries consistent once a structure is chosen.

## State Management
- Use `Cubit` from `flutter_bloc` for feature state management.
- Keep ephemeral widget state local to the widget.
- Move business state and async workflows into Cubits.
- Define explicit states for loading, success, empty, and error phases.
- Keep each Cubit's states in a separate `*_state.dart` file.
- Avoid overloading one state object with unrelated concerns.
- Prefer one Cubit per screen, flow, or feature boundary unless a smaller split is clearly justified.

## Dependency Management
- Use `GetIt` for dependency injection.
- Centralize registrations in one DI module or small set of DI modules.
- Prefer constructor injection over hidden global lookups.
- Keep object creation out of UI code unless the dependency is trivial and local.
- Register long-lived services once and keep lightweight objects easy to replace in tests.
- Do not add ad-hoc `GetIt` registrations inside feature code.

## Routing
- Use `GoRouter` with a central router configuration.
- Prefer named routes for clarity and maintainability.
- Keep navigation decisions out of low-level widgets when they affect application flow.
- Guard protected flows explicitly and handle invalid navigation states gracefully.

## Data Layer
- Keep remote, local, and cache concerns separated.
- Convert external payloads into app models through explicit mappers or adapters.
- Do not pass raw JSON or loosely typed maps through the app.
- Treat repositories as coordination boundaries, not dumping grounds for business logic.

## Domain Logic
- Keep business logic in dedicated use cases, controllers, or services.
- Give each unit one clear responsibility.
- Validate inputs and handle failure paths explicitly.
- Return domain-friendly results instead of leaking transport or storage details upward.

## Entities & Value Types
- Entities must extend `Equatable`.
- Immutable value types should extend `Equatable` when value equality is expected.
- Include all meaningful fields in `props`.
- Keep entities focused on domain data, not framework or transport concerns.
- Keep entities free of UI, framework, and transport dependencies other than `Equatable`.

## UI Guidelines
- Keep screens composed from small, focused widgets.
- Extract reusable UI pieces instead of growing large screen files.
- Prefer predictable layouts and clear visual hierarchy over deeply nested widget trees.
- Keep styling centralized through theme, tokens, or shared constants.
- Make loading, empty, and error states first-class parts of the UI.

## Errors & Logging
- Fail loudly in development and gracefully in production.
- Surface user-facing errors with actionable messages where possible.
- Log at important boundaries such as request start, success, retry, and failure.
- Do not swallow exceptions without either handling or rethrowing them intentionally.

## Networking
- Keep API clients thin and focused on transport concerns.
- Normalize responses and errors before they reach the UI layer.
- Handle connectivity, timeouts, retries, and cancellation intentionally.
- Avoid embedding request-building logic throughout feature code.

## Testing
- Unit test cubits, use cases, repositories, mappers, and data layer.
- Widget test important UI states and user flows.
- Prefer deterministic tests with mocked dependencies over networked or timing-sensitive tests.
- Add regression coverage for bug fixes and risky logic changes.

## Code Style
- Use descriptive names for classes, methods, variables, and files.
- Prefer strong typing and explicit models over `dynamic`.
- Favor early returns and shallow control flow.
- Add comments only when they explain intent, constraints, or non-obvious tradeoffs.
- Match existing formatting and naming patterns in the project.

## Patterns to Repeat
- Clear separation between UI, state, domain logic, and data access.
- Explicit mapping between external data and internal models.
- Small, composable widgets and focused classes.
- `Cubit` per feature with explicit state transitions.
- Separate `*_cubit.dart` and `*_state.dart` files per feature.
- Centralized configuration for `GoRouter`, `GetIt`, and shared services.
- Observable error handling and testable async flows.

## Patterns to Avoid
- Business logic inside widgets.
- Passing loosely typed maps through multiple layers.
- Hidden global dependencies and ad-hoc service lookup in feature code.
- Large files that mix UI, networking, persistence, and business rules.
- Silent failures, background side effects, and untracked async work.

